TY  - JOUR
T1  - Decision Theory Applied to a Linear Panel Data Model
AU  - Chamberlain, Gary
AU  - Moreira, Marcelo J.
Y1  - 2009/01/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA6869
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 107
EP  - 133
VL  - 77
IS  - 1
KW  - Autoregression
KW  - fixed effects
KW  - incidental parameters
KW  - invariance
KW  - minimax
KW  - correlated random effects
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA6869
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper applies some general concepts in decision theory to a linear panel data model. A simple version of the model is an autoregression with a separate intercept for each unit in the cross section, with errors that are independent and identically distributed with a normal distribution. There is a parameter of interest ? and a nuisance parameter τ, a N?K matrix, where N is the cross-section sample size. The focus is on dealing with the incidental parameters problem created by a potentially high-dimension nuisance parameter. We adopt a ?fixed-effects? approach that seeks to protect against any sequence of incidental parameters. We transform τ to (δ, ?, ?), where δ is a J?K matrix of coefficients from the least-squares projection of τ on a N?J matrix x of strictly exogenous variables, ? is a K?K symmetric, positive semidefinite matrix obtained from the residual sums of squares and cross-products in the projection of τ on x, and ? is a (N?J) ?K matrix whose columns are orthogonal and have unit length. The model is invariant under the actions of a group on the sample space and the parameter space, and we find a maximal invariant statistic. The distribution of the maximal invariant statistic does not depend upon ?. There is a unique invariant distribution for ?. We use this invariant distribution as a prior distribution to obtain an integrated likelihood function. It depends upon the observation only through the maximal invariant statistic. We use the maximal invariant statistic to construct a marginal likelihood function, so we can eliminate ? by integration with respect to the invariant prior distribution or by working with the marginal likelihood function. The two approaches coincide. Decision rules based on the invariant distribution for ? have a minimax property. Given a loss function that does not depend upon ? and given a prior distribution for (?, δ, ?), we show how to minimize the average?with respect to the prior distribution for (?, δ, ?)?of the maximum risk, where the maximum is with respect to ?. There is a family of prior distributions for (δ, ?) that leads to a simple closed form for the integrated likelihood function. This integrated likelihood function coincides with the likelihood function for a normal, correlated random-effects model. Under random sampling, the corresponding quasi maximum likelihood estimator is consistent for ? as N?∞, with a standard limiting distribution. The limit results do not require normality or homoskedasticity (conditional on x) assumptions.
ER  - 

